result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: This case dismissed and read in as part of the disposition this date in 15CM173 and 15CM206.

Defendant James B. Tulley in court with attorney Lisa A McDougal. Prosecuting Atty Amy Elizabeth Forehand appeared for State of Wisconsin.  3 cases called together for status:  15CM194, 15CM173, and 15CM206.  Atty. M informs the Court that the parties have reached an agreement for resolution whereby def will plead to count 1 of 15CM173/dc and three counts of bail jumping in 15CM206 for a sentence that includes 2 years probation for the dc and two of the bail jumping counts and 30 days jail (straight sentence) for the third bail jumping count; remaining counts and 15CM194 to be dismissed.  Def pleads guilty to the four counts indicated.  Court's colloquy on pleas.  Finding of guilty.

14 days credit due in 15CM206 (to be applied to the straight jail sentence).

Sentence for 15CM173 and counts 1 and 2 of 15CM206:  2 years probation on withheld sentence.  Pay costs.  1 set for each case.  Attend, pay for, and succ. complete 24- to 26-wk d.a. program.  No contact with TB.  Count 3 of 15CM206 - 30 days jail as a straight sentence with 14 days credit.  Remaining counts and 15CM194 dismissed/read in.  Huber granted.

Defendant James B. Tulley appeared by video means. Prosecuting Atty Amy Elizabeth Forehand appeared for State of Wisconsin. Attorney Lisa A McDougal in court for Defendant James B. Tulley.
